  <content>
    <para id="para-00001">Like alkenes (<link document="m00092">Section 8.4</link> and <link document="m00093">Section 8.5</link>), alkynes can be hydrated by either of two methods. Direct addition of water catalyzed by mercury(II) ion yields the Markovnikov product, and indirect addition of water by a hydroboration–oxidation sequence yields the non-Markovnikov product.</para>
    <section id="sect-00001">
    <title>Mercury(II)-Catalyzed Hydration of Alkynes</title>
    <para id="para-00002">Alkynes don’t react directly with aqueous acid but will undergo hydration readily in the presence of mercury(II) sulfate as a Lewis acid catalyst. The reaction occurs with Markovnikov regiochemistry, so the −OH group adds to the more highly substituted carbon and the −H attaches to the less highly substituted one.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein 1-hexyne reacts in the presence of water sulfuric acid and mercury sulfate to yield “an enol” that further yields “2-Hexanone (78%).” The structure of 1-Hexyne shows a methyl group bonded to three consecutive methylene groups and bonded to a carbon triple bonded to a methine group. An enol shown in parentheses shows a methyl group bonded to three consecutive methylene groups bonded to a carbon that is double bonded to a methylene group. The carbon is bonded to a hydroxyl group at the top. The structure of 2-Hexanone shows a methyl group bonded to three consecutive methylene groups bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to a methyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_09_04_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00003">Interestingly, the actual product isolated from alkyne hydration is not a vinylic alcohol, or <term id="term-00001">enol</term> (<emphasis effect="italics">ene</emphasis> + <emphasis effect="italics">ol</emphasis>), but is instead a ketone. Although the enol is an intermediate in the reaction, it immediately rearranges into a ketone by a process called <emphasis effect="italics">keto–enol tautomerism.</emphasis> The individual keto and enol forms are said to be <term id="term-00002">tautomers</term>, a word used to describe two isomers that undergo spontaneous interconversion accompanied by the change in position of a hydrogen. With few exceptions, the keto–enol tautomeric equilibrium lies on the side of the ketone; enols are almost never isolated. We’ll look more closely at this equilibrium in [link]Section 22.1[/link].</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reversible structures. The first structure is an “enol tautomer (less favored)” and the second structure is a “keto tautomer (more favored).” The enol tautomer shows two carbons double bonded to each other. The top carbon is bonded to a hydroxyl group and shows a free bond. The bottom carbon shows two free bonds. The keto tautomer shows two carbons single bonded to each other. The top carbon is double bonded to an oxygen atom and shows a free bond. The bottom carbon is bonded to a hydrogen atom and shows two free bonds.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_09_04_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00004">As shown in <link target-id="fig-00003"/>, the mechanism of the mercury(II)-catalyzed alkyne hydration reaction is analogous to the oxymercuration reaction of alkenes (<link document="m00092">Section 8.4</link>). Electrophilic addition of mercury(II) ion to the alkyne gives a vinylic cation, which reacts with water and loses a proton to yield a mercury-containing enol intermediate. In contrast with alkene oxymercuration, however, no treatment with NaBH<sub>4</sub> is necessary to remove the mercury. The acidic reaction conditions alone are sufficient to effect replacement of mercury by hydrogen. Tautomerization then gives the ketone.</para>
    <figure class="mechanism-figure scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <title>MECHANISM</title>
    <media alt="An illustration shows five steps involved in the formation of an intermediate enol. Step “1” reads: “the alkyne uses a pair of electrons to attack the electrophilic mercury (II) ion yielding a mercury containing vinylic carbocation intermediate”; the corresponding structure shows R bonded to C having a blue triple bond with carbon bonded to hydrogen; a pink arrow from the blue triple bond shows “green mercury sulfate” Hg2+ SO4 to the power two minus; the structure of carbocation shows R bonded to carbon cation having a blue double bond with another carbon bonded to hydrogen and green mercury sulfate Hg+SO4 to the power two minus; a pink arrow points from pink water molecule having an oxygen with two pairs of electrons to the carbon cation. The forthcoming structures of steps “2” to “4” are shown enclosed in horizontal parentheses. The step “2” reads: “nucleophilic attack of water on the carbocation forms a C-O bond and yields a protonated mercury containing enol”; the corresponding structure shows carbon sharing blue double bond with another carbon the left side carbon shares an upward bond with pink oxygen cation bonded to two hydrogens; the carbon at right side is bonded to hydrogen and green mercury sulfate Hg+ SO4 to the power two minus; a pink water molecule having oxygen with two pairs of electrons is shown at the upper right corner; a pink arrow points from oxygen to pink hydrogen and another pink arrow from the bond between hydrogen and oxygen to the oxygen cation. Step “3” reads: “abstraction of proton from the protonated enol by water gives an organomercury compound”; the corresponding reaction shows a pink hydronium ion and a structure comprising of a carbon sharing a blue double bond with another carbon; the left side carbon shows an upward bond with pink hydroxyl group and downward bond with R; the carbon at the right side is bonded to hydrogen and green mercury sulfate. Step “4” reads “replacement of mercury Hg2+ by proton occurs to give a neutral enol”; the corresponding reaction shows formation of water and a structure comprising of a carbon sharing blue double bond with another carbon; the left side carbon shares an upward bond with a pink hydroxyl group and a downward bond with “R”; the carbon at right side shows a bond with hydrogen and a pink hydrogen. Step “5” reads: “the enol undergoes tautomerization to give the final ketone product”; the resulting structure is shown outside the horizontal parentheses; it comprises of a carbonyl group having pink oxygen the carbon bonds to “R” on the left side and on the right side carbon bonds to another carbon bonded to three hydrogens of which two are pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_09_04_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism of the mercury(II)-catalyzed hydration of an alkyne to yield a ketone.</emphasis> The reaction occurs through initial formation of an intermediate enol, which tautomerizes to the ketone.</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00005">A mixture of both possible ketones results when an unsymmetrically substituted internal alkyne (<m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>RC</m:mtext><m:mo>≡</m:mo><m:mtext>CR</m:mtext><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math>) is hydrated. The reaction is therefore most useful when applied to a terminal alkyne (<m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>RC</m:mtext><m:mo>≡</m:mo><m:mtext>CH</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math>) because only a methyl ketone is formed.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactions. The first reaction shows “an internal alkyne” reacting in the presence of a pink hydronium cation and mercury sulfate to yield a mixture. The alkyne shows an R bonded to C triple bonded to another C bonded to R’. The mixture comprises of two structures; the first structure shows R bonded to a carbonyl group having pink oxygen the carbon of carbonyl to its right is bonded to methylene group attached to R’; the second structure shows RCH2 bonded to a carbonyl group having pink oxygen and the carbon of carbonyl group is bonded to R’. The second reaction shows a terminal alkyne reacting in the presence of a pink hydronium cation and mercury sulfate to yield a methyl ketone. The alkyne shows R bonded to a carbon triple bonded to a methine group. The methyl ketone shows an R bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_09_04_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
