    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Hydroboration–Oxidation of Alkynes</title>
    <para id="para-00008">Borane adds rapidly to an alkyne just as it does to an alkene, and the resulting vinylic borane can be oxidized by H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub> to give an enol, which tautomerizes to either a ketone or an aldehyde, depending on the alkyne. Hydroboration–oxidation of an internal alkyne such as 3-hexyne is straightforward and gives a ketone, but hydroboration–oxidation of a terminal alkyne is more complex because two molecules of borane often add to the triple bond, complicating the situation. To prevent this double addition, a bulky, sterically encumbered borane such as bis(1,2-dimethylpropyl)borane, known commonly as disiamylborane is used in place of BH<sub>3</sub>. When a terminal alkyne such as 1-butene reacts with disiamylborane, addition to the triple bond occurs normally, but a second addition is hindered by the bulk of the dialkylborane. Oxidation with H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub> then gives an enol, which tautomerizes to the aldehyde.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustrations shows two reactions. In the first reaction three moles of “an internal alkyne” reacts in the presence of green borane BH3 and THF to yield “a vinylic borane” in parentheses which reacts in the presence of hydrogen peroxide water molecule and sodium hydroxide to yield three moles of “an enol” in parentheses. The enol reacts to yield three moles of “3-Hexanone.” The structural formula of alkyne shows a methyl group bonded to a methylene group attached to a carbon triple bonded to another carbon bonded to a methylene group attached to a methyl group. The structure of vinylic borane shows an open 6-membered ring with two hydrogen atoms a boron and four carbons. The carbons are double bonded to the adjacent carbons. Each carbon is bonded to an ethyl group. The boron is single bonded to a carbon bonded to an ethyl group and double bonded to a methine group bonded to an ethyl group. The structure of the enol shows two carbons double bonded to each other; the carbon on the left is bonded to a green hydrogen and an ethyl group; the carbon on the right is bonded to a pink hydroxyl group and an ethyl group. The structure of 3-hexanone shows a methyl group bonded to two methylene groups attached to carbonyl group having a pink oxygen; the carbon of carbonyl group is bonded to an ethyl group. The second reaction shows a terminal alkyne (1-hexyne) reacting in the presence of green borane and THF to yield an intermediate structure that reacts in the presence of hydrogen peroxide and water molecule at pH 8 to yield “hexanal (70%).” The structure of 1-hexyne shows a methyl group bonded to three consecutive methylene groups bonded to a carbon triple bonded to a methine group. The intermediate structure shows a methyl group bonded to four methylene groups bonded to a methine group. The methine group is bonded to two boron atoms. Each boron is bonded to two R groups. The structure of hexanal shows a methyl group bonded to four consecutive methylene groups bonded to an aldehyde group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_09_04_07.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
        <para id="para-00009">The hydroboration–oxidation sequence is complementary to the direct, mercury(II)-catalyzed hydration reaction of a terminal alkyne because different products result. Direct hydration with aqueous acid and mercury(II) sulfate leads to a methyl ketone, whereas hydroboration–oxidation of the same terminal alkyne leads to an aldehyde.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactions of a terminal alkyne. In the first reaction it reacts in the presence of water sulfuric acid and mercury sulfate to form “a methyl ketone”; in the second reaction the terminal alkyne reacts in the presence of borane THF and hydrogen peroxide to yield “an aldehyde.” The structure of alkyne shows R bonded to C triple bonded to a methine group. The methyl ketone shows R bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group. The structure of an aldehyde shows a carbon bonded to R two hydrogens an aldehyde group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_09_04_009.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
